{
  "response_text": "The simulation of the agent-based model tracks the average total livestock across the heterogeneous population of households over 100 timesteps. The dynamic begins at an initial value of 90.0 at timestep 0. A pronounced downward trajectory dominates the first phase, with the metric declining steadily to reach a distinct minimum of 41.01 at timestep 37. Statistical trend analysis confirms a significant decreasing trend for the first half of this descent. Following the nadir at timestep 37, the trajectory shifts; rolling window analyses detect significant increasing trends beginning around timestep 44. By the conclusion of the simulation at timestep 100, the average total livestock recovers slightly to a final value of 47.55. This dynamic reflects an initial rapid adjustment period where herd sizes are reduced, likely in response to initial conditions relative to pasture carrying capacity, followed by a phase of stabilization and modest regrowth as the learning agents adapt their stocking rates within the social-ecological system."
}

